David Pearson was one of NASCAR's most popular drivers ever. He won 19 Cup championships and over 200 races during his career. But this race in particular stands out because of how he beat Richard Petty on the last lap. Pearson was leading when the caution flag came out with three laps to go. When the green flag dropped, Petty tried to run him down, but Pearson had other plans. As they went through turn four, Petty tried to make a pass on the inside, but Pearson closed the door. Then, as they were coming off turn four, Petty made contact with Pearson's rear bumper. That caused Pearson to spin around into the infield grass. The caution came out again, giving Pearson enough time to change tires before the next restart. When the green flag dropped, Petty jumped out to a quick lead, but Pearson wouldn't give up. With two laps remaining, Pearson caught up to Petty and took the lead as they crossed the start -finish line. Pearson would hold on to win by less than a tenth of a second. It was the closest win in NASCAR history at the time. And it wasn't until 2003 that anyone else even came close to winning by that little margin. In fact, it wouldn't happen until 2014 when Kevin Harvick edged Martin Truex Jr. by .008 seconds. So if you want to see some of the best finishes ever, look no further than the Coke Zero Sugar 400. For more top five moments, click the link below and subscribe to our YouTube...

Hey guys, welcome back to the channel. Today we're going to be looking at the armless darce choke. So this is one of my favorite chokeholds in jiu -jitsu. It's a very powerful chokehold. It can be used from standing or it can also be used when you have your opponent on their knees. So I'm going to show you both ways how to do it today. Let's get into it. All right, so first thing we want to look at here is our stance. We don't want to stand too close because if he falls down like that, that's not good for us. We need to make sure we've got enough space to work with. If we're standing too close, then there's no way he's going to fall over. He'll just fall straight onto me. And now I'm stuck. I'm trying to escape but there's nowhere to go. He's still holding me tight. Nowhere to go. There's nothing I can do. So what we want to do is we want to keep some space between us. That gives him room to move around. If he does fall down, then we can come up behind his head and start working our choke. Okay? So let's take a look at the armless darts choke. First things first, we're going to grab his wrist. Now, if he has his hand free, this is where we would normally grab his wrist and pull it across our body. Instead, try to move along with the subject as much as possible. This will help keep the camera steady and create less shaking in the image. A good way to avoid rope tangling is to use a rope clamp. The rope clamp is attached to the climbers' rope before the start of the climb. It should be attached about 2 meters above the ground. When ascending, you pull the rope through the rope clamp and attach it to the carabiner. Now you can secure the climber with the brake hand below the carabiner. If there was no rope clamp, you would have to secure the climber with the brake hand up. In addition, it is much more difficult to get the rope untangled. To untangle the rope, you first release the brake hand from the brake rope. Then you pull the brake rope outwards until the knot comes loose. After that, you can simply re -attach the brake hand to the brake cable. We hope we could help you with our tips on preventing rope tangling and ensure your safety....

If you have any questions, leave them down below.  Alright guys, so one thing I wanted to talk about today is eye focus. Now when we're talking about eye focus, we're talking about where your eyes are focused during the shot. A lot of people say they focus on their arrow. That's fine. Some people even say they focus on their target. That's also fine. What I do when I'm focusing during the shot is I focus right behind my arrow. So as soon as I draw my bowstring, I look through my peep site and I focus right behind my arrow. And once I let go of the nock, I'll follow the arrow until it hits its mark. And then I'll stop following it. The reason why I do that is because as soon as I release the nock, there's a little bit of movement in the string. There's a little bit of movement in the bow. There's a little bit of movement in my hand. And there's a little bit of movement in my body. So if I try to follow the arrow too long, by the time I stop following it, all those movements have already happened. So I might miss my target. If I just follow it until it hits its mark, then I can let go of the nock and everything else stays where it needs to stay. So give that a try. Let me know how it works for you. Just look through your peep site,...

I think it's important to remember that leg yield is not only good for correcting symmetry, but it's also very good at helping develop the self -carriage of the horse. So as soon as they learn to carry themselves in their own body, they don't need us so much anymore. They can carry themselves and stay steady on our hands. And that's where leg yield comes into play. It helps them develop that self -carriage. It helps them learn to use their back legs better. It helps them learn to use their hind legs better. It helps them stay balanced. It helps them stay straighter. Leg yield is a great exercise for that. Now, if you have a horse who has a tendency to lean out or who tends to fall asleep on his neck when you're doing leg yielding, you might want to try something different. Maybe you could try shoulders in instead of leg yield. Or maybe you could try... circles around yourself or circles around a cone instead of leg yielding. But remember, leg yielding is a great way to address symmetry issues as well as help develop the self -carriage of the horse. The next step is to tie the handbrake. There are different ways to do so. We will start off with the most common way of tying the handbrake in top -rope mode. First, you hold the rope coming from the climber and the one going up the wall in both hands. Then you pull down the climbers' rope until there is enough slack to tie the handbrake. Now you form a loop with the cable coming from the climber and pass it under the other loop. Pull tight and adjust the length of the loops. It should be about 10 centimeters long. If they're too short, they won't work properly. And if they're too long, they might get caught on something while climbing. Afterwards, you pull the rope coming from the climber again until there is enough slack to tie another half -mast throw. Again, pass the rope underneath the first loop and tighten everything up. In case you want to lower someone, there are some differences compared to lowering yourself. Firstly, you don't use the top rope but the bottom one. Secondly, when you lower yourself, you always use the same hand for pulling the rope. But when you want to lower someone else, you switch hands after each throw. This way, you avoid accidentally getting stuck by the rope. So let's go through the steps once more....

The 1976 Olympics were held in Montreal, Canada. It was here that Edwin Moses made his mark on the track and field world by winning four consecutive Olympic titles over the hurdles. Moses' first hurdle race at these Games came in the semifinals where he easily qualified for the final. In the final, Moses ran away from the pack early and never looked back. He finished with a time of 48 .5 seconds, a new Olympic record. His victory over his closest competitor was almost five seconds. Moses had now won four straight gold medals in the hurdle events. A feat no other hurdler had done before or since.  Moses would go on to win another gold medal...

I know that sounds obvious, but it's very important. So, if I'm asking myself, am I able to stop my horse without my reins? And I'm doing that by using my seat, my legs, and my hands. I want to talk about the gimbal versus the max lens mod. So if you don't know what these things are, here's one right here. So this is the gimbal. It's basically like a little stabilizer. You can put your GoPro on there and then when you're riding or whatever, it keeps everything nice and smooth. And then the other thing is called the max lens mod. And it does exactly what it says. It makes your camera lens bigger. So let me show you how both of them work. Then we'll go out and do a comparison between them. So first up is the gimbal. Now, I got this from Amazon. It was $30. There's tons of different ones online. They all pretty much work the same way. They're all battery powered. The only difference is some of them have buttons where you can turn off the stabilization and others don't. But essentially, you just plug your GoPro into one side, turn it on, and then when you start moving around, everything stays nice and smooth. So as long as you keep moving forward, everything should stay nice and stable. Now, if you stop, or if you move too fast, like if you hit a big jump or something, sometimes it doesn't quite catch up with you. But overall, it works pretty well. One downside though is that it adds a bit more weight to your helmet. Next up is the Max Lens Mod. Now, this is actually made by GoPro themselves. It costs about $50 Canadian. What it does is it basically takes the standard lens cover off your camera and replaces it with a larger one. That means you get a wider field of view. As far as the quality goes, there isn't any noticeable difference. However, because it's not actually a lens, but rather just a piece of plastic, it's less likely to get scratched than the actual lens itself. Also, since it's made by GoPro, it fits perfectly onto their cameras. If you use another brand, you might run into issues with fitment. Overall, I think it's worth getting if you plan on using your GoPro a lot. Alright guys, now let's head back down to the bottom and compare the two together.
